  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Responding to Emergency WASH needs of IDPs in MMC/Jere, Magumeri and Monguno, Borno State, NE Nigeria</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Fighting between the Nigeria Security Forces and Armed Opposition groups (AOGs) from November 2018 led to significant population influx into Monguno, MMC and Jere LGAs which resulted in overstretching existing WASH services provided by partners in already congested IDP camps and settlements. Since January 2019, the IRC has been responding to this emergency through emergency WASH across MMC, Jere and Monguno LGAs. On 4th April 2019 a fire outbreak in Gajigana town in Magumeri LGA affected 3,000 households (15,000 people) who lost their shelters, food reserves, personal belongings as well as their sanitation facilities.   

This project seeks to improve the general health and wellbeing of the newly displaced population of approximately 25,000 individuals by ensuring people have equitable access to safe water sanitation and also be provided with the necessary supplies and knowledge needed to prevent WASH related diseases . The specific objective of this project is to protect people from water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) related diseases. With NHF funding, the IRC scale up the emergency WASH response activities in new Fulatari IDP camp in Monguno LGA, Teachers village (TV) IDP camp in MMC as well as provide urgent lifesaving support in Gajigana town in Magumeri LGA. This project will prioritize the needs of vulnerable groups especially women, girls and children and ensure their most critical WASH needs and concerns are addressed during the inception and implementation of the whole project. The IRC will implement this project with close coordination of the Borno state WASH Sector working group led by the ministry of water resources and seconded by UNICEF. Also the IRC will work closely with SEMA, NEMA, CCCM, Protection Sector working group as well as with other WASH actors.</narrative>
  </description>
